(80, '2025-01-22', 'The Perfect oatmeal Cookies', 'A Healthy and Delicious Treat for Any Occasion', 'Who can resist a batch of warm, chewy oatmeal cookies fresh out of the oven? Packed with wholesome oats and a touch of sweetness, these cookies strike the perfect balance between indulgence and nutrition. Whether you\'re looking for a quick snack or a dessert to share, this recipe will win over your taste buds and your heart.', 'Ingredients\r\n\r\n1 cup (100g) rolled oats\r\n1 cup (125g) all-purpose flour\r\n1/2 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1/4 teaspoon salt\r\n1/2 cup (115g) unsalted butter, softened\r\n1/2 cup (100g) brown sugar, packed\r\n1/4 cup (50g) granulated sugar\r\n1 large egg\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n1/2 cup (75g) raisins or chocolate chips (optional)\r\nInstructions\r\n\r\nPreheat the Oven\r\nPreheat your oven to 350°F (175°C) and line a baking sheet with parchment paper.\r\n\r\nMix Dry Ingredients\r\nIn a medium bowl, whisk together the oats, flour, baking soda, and salt. Set aside.\r\n\r\nCream Butter and Sugars\r\nIn a large mixing bowl, use a hand mixer or stand mixer to beat the softened butter, brown sugar, and granulated sugar until light and fluffy.\r\n\r\nAdd Wet Ingredients\r\nBeat in the egg and vanilla extract until fully combined.\r\n\r\nCombine Wet and Dry\r\nGradually add the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients, mixing until just combined. If desired, fold in raisins or chocolate chips.\r\n\r\nScoop and Shape\r\nScoop tablespoons of dough and roll them into balls. Place them on the prepared baking sheet, leaving about 2 inches between each cookie. Flatten slightly with your hand.\r\n\r\nBake\r\nBake for 10–12 minutes, or until the edges are golden brown and the centers look slightly undercooked. They will continue to firm up as they cool.\r\n\r\nCool and Enjoy\r\nLet the cookies cool on the baking sheet for 5 minutes before transferring them to a wire rack to cool completely. Serve and enjoy!\r\n\r\nTips\r\n\r\nFor a chewier texture, chill the dough for 30 minutes before baking.\r\nAdd a pinch of cinnamon or nutmeg for extra warmth and flavor.\r\nYour oatmeal cookies are now ready to enjoy! Perfect with a cup of tea, coffee, or a glass of milk.', 'uploads\\Cookies.webp', 13),
(81, '2025-01-23', 'The Art of Finding Balance in a Busy World', 'How to Prioritize Yourself Without Sacrificing Your Goals', 'In today’s fast-paced society, finding balance can feel like an impossible task. With work deadlines, social obligations, and personal aspirations pulling us in different directions, it’s easy to lose sight of what truly matters. This post will explore practical strategies to regain control and prioritize your well-being without compromising your goals.', 'Start Your Day with Intention\r\nBegin each morning by setting clear goals for the day. A simple five-minute journaling session can help you outline what’s important and mentally prepare for the challenges ahead.\r\n\r\nLearn to Say No\r\nOne of the most powerful ways to find balance is by learning to say no. Evaluate your commitments and ask yourself: “Does this align with my priorities?” Saying no to what doesn’t serve you makes room for what truly matters.\r\n\r\nEmbrace Small Wins\r\nBalance doesn’t mean perfection. Celebrate small achievements, whether it’s completing a task, spending time with loved ones, or simply taking a break.\r\n\r\nDisconnect to Reconnect\r\nIn a world dominated by screens, stepping away from technology can be a game-changer. Dedicate specific times to unplug, reflect, and connect with the present moment.\r\n\r\nBy implementing these steps, you’ll not only find balance but also rediscover the joy in everyday life. Remember, achieving balance isn’t about doing it all; it’s about doing what matters most.\r\n\r\n', 'uploads\\art-of-finding.webp', 17),
(82, '2025-01-23', 'The Power of Small Habits for Big Changes', 'Transform Your Life One Step at a Time', 'We often think big changes require drastic actions. But the truth is, it’s the small, consistent habits we cultivate that lead to lasting transformation. This post dives into the science behind small habits and provides practical tips to implement them into your daily life.', 'Why Small Habits Matter\r\nSmall habits compound over time, creating significant results. For example, reading just one page a day can lead to finishing several books in a year. By focusing on manageable actions, you set yourself up for sustainable progress.\r\n\r\nStart with One Change\r\nPick one habit you want to build and start small. If your goal is to exercise, begin with 5 minutes a day. Starting small reduces overwhelm and builds confidence as you succeed.\r\n\r\nMake It Easy and Accessible\r\nRemove barriers to your new habit. If you want to drink more water, keep a water bottle nearby at all times. Simplifying the process increases the chances of sticking to it.\r\n\r\nCelebrate Small Wins\r\nRecognize and reward yourself for completing even the tiniest steps. This positive reinforcement strengthens the habit and keeps you motivated.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nBig transformations don’t happen overnight. They are the result of small, consistent efforts over time. Start today with one small habit and watch how it shapes your future. Remember, success is built one step at a time.', 'uploads\\small-habit.webp', 14),
